{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"05aef3d2-31b7-4fd9-a155-9d546bf07af5","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9**, which supports the modern patterns. Here's the recommended approach:\n\n- **Constructor** — for sync initialization and `TestContext` injection\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — for async initialization (supports `async Task`)\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private readonly MyHelper _helper;\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;          // injected by MSTest\n        _helper = new MyHelper();           // sync setup\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitAsync()\n    {\n        await _helper.ConnectAsync();       // async setup\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        await _helper.DisconnectAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_helper);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- MSTest 3.x supports **constructor injection** of `TestContext` — no need for the legacy `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property.\n- Put sync setup in the **constructor**, async setup in **`[TestInitialize]`**.\n- Both `[TestInitialize]` and `[TestCleanup]` support `async Task`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0550c825-e1e6-4c9b-a784-61d516f2c42a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or the `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property. In MSTest v3+, constructor injection is supported.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` attribute on a method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` on an `async Task` method. MSTest v3 supports async TestInitialize.\n\nActually, in MSTest 3.x, the recommended modern pattern is:\n\n\n- **TestContext**: Inject via constructor (`public MyTests(TestContext testContext)`) — this is the newer pattern in MSTest 3.x.\n- **[TestInitialize]**: Can be sync or async, but you can only have one `[TestInitialize]` method total, so if you need async initialization, make that single method async.\n\nThe recommended approach in MSTest v3 is to use the constructor for synchronous setup and TestContext injection, then use an async `[TestInitialize]` method for any asynchronous initialization work.","outputTokens":736,"requestId":"7683:3EF0C4:BA0B2E:D81A22:69F2B04E"},"id":"e0f9871f-c395-4847-bdac-fe0290e6a30b","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:29:02.774Z","parentId":"746492c9-b4da-480a-96f0-8090ec9ef23e"}
